<HEADLINE>
<P>
BAUSCH & LOMB PRESIDENT PICKED FOR GM BOARD AND EXECUTIVE POST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 General Motors Corp. on Wednesday appointed an outsider to head its vast North 
American sales, service and marketing operations. 
</P>
<P>
 Ronald L. Zarrella, the 45-year-old president of Bausch & Lomb Corp., will 
become a GM vice president and group executive Dec. 12, and will join the board 
of directors of General Motors Acceptance Corp., the financing arm. 
</P>
<P>
 Zarrella will oversee the management of the Buick, Cadillac, Chevrolet, 
Oldsmobile, Pontiac and GMC Truck divisions, which account for about $100 
billion a year in sales. He'll also be in charge of GM of Canada, GM Service 
Parts Operations and North American marketing and advertising staffs. He 
succeeds J. Michael Losh, who in July became an executive vice president and 
GM's chief financial officer. 
</P>
<P>
 GM's stock rose 62.5 cents to $39.625 a share in active trading on the New 
York Stock Exchange Wednesday. 
</P>
