<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: REGION; COUNTY LIBRARIES RESTORING HOURS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Many South Bay libraries were expanding their services beginning this week 
after almost two years of reduced hours, scaled-back library staffs and slashed 
materials budgets. 
</P>
<P>
 An injection of $22.5 million into the Los Angeles County Library system 
budget by the Board of Supervisors last month made it possible to restore hours 
and services to libraries in Gardena, Lawndale, Lomita, Manhattan Beach, 
Hawthorne and Lennox. 
</P>
<P>
 Library officials say a lack of staff has delayed restoring hours at libraries 
in Carson and Hermosa Beach, although officials expect to have them running on 
full schedule by the end of the month.  
</P>
<P>
 The new funds will mean more librarians to handle special requests, new 
reference books and materials at most libraries, plus updated technical and 
clinical guides at the library's resource and research centers, said library 
spokeswoman Jean Alexander. 
</P>
<P>
 Library officials were forced to cut hours, staff and materials two years ago 
when state officials shifted funds away from county governments -- and thus the 
library budget -- to other areas. That money, which accounted for almost half 
of the library system's budget, has not been replaced by the state, Alexander 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Since then, the county has given the library district several million dollars 
a year but not enough to cover a continued drain of library revenues by the 
state, Alexander said. 
</P>
<P>
 Late this summer, library officials attended city council meetings asking 
councils to approve a special tax to keep the system solvent. The tax, which 
would have cost homeowners about $28.50 a year, was overwhelmingly turned down 
by the South Bay cities that voted on it. Carson and Lomita approved the tax. 
</P>
<P>
 But county officials bailed out the library system. Library officials say the 
money will only last through June, and county officials have pledged to give 
only $10 million next year. Expanded Library Hours 
</P>
<P>
 The county library system is increasing the number of days and the hours its 
branches will be open. 
</P>
