</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
COOK'S TIP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A nonreactive pan is one made from a material that won't react with acidic 
ingredients. Nonstick, stainless-steel, lined or anodized aluminum, lined 
copper and enameled cast-iron are the most common types. Avoid unlined 
aluminum, copper and cast-iron pans when a nonreactive pot is specified in a 
recipe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA111794-0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 099644 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
November 17, 1994, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Food; Part H; Page 32; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1414 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOME COOK: THANKSGIVING; EVERYTHING BUT THE BIRD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARION CUNNINGHAM 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Amid all the preparations for a holiday meal, it's easy to lose sight of the 
basic reason for the celebration. The appeal of Thanksgiving is in the 
simplicity of the day -- being with people we care about and sharing good food. 
For those of us who like to cook, there is the extra pleasure of arising early 
Thanksgiving morning, rolling up our sleeves and starting to cook. 
</P>
<P>
 To make things easier, the table will have been set the night before, some of 
the small preparations will have been completed and the pie crusts will be 
ready and waiting to be filled and baked. Once the pies are in the oven, it 
will be time to prepare the vegetable side dishes. 
</P>
<P>
 I find that I am increasingly attracted to simple foods, and that over the 
years I've slowly changed my vegetable side dishes accordingly. For example, I 
have dropped fresh coconut or bits of orange sections from the carrots. These 
days I simply cook young carrots and finish them with butter and parsley. 
</P>
<P>
 Beets, which are naturally sweet, are mixed with capers and vinegar for a 
little contrast and snap. A traditional Thanksgiving dinner is enhanced by a 
compote of winter fruits, whose full flavor is tinged with a pleasant sourness. 
Baked squash with maple syrup is a real American dish that can be a pleasant 
change from sweet potatoes or yams, and cabbage with pine nuts will surprise 
anyone who has never given that kingly vegetable its due (it is also one of the 
quickest dishes to make). 
</P>
<P>
 And then there are pearl onions, without which many feel Thanksgiving is 
incomplete. In this version, they are baked in a creamy onion sauce with a 
crisp topping of bread crumbs. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Today, more than ever, most of us have nearby farmers markets or greengrocers 
that take pride in offering an abundance of very fresh produce. And when you're 
using such basically good ingredients, you don't have to worry about fussing 
with them too much. In these recipes, Mother Nature has done most of the work 
for us, providing us with another blessing for which we gather to give thanks. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Since it cooks for less than half a minute, this cabbage retains its lovely 
green color and crisp texture. Toasted pine nuts look pretty on top and add a 
little crunch.  
</P>
<P>
 CABBAGE WITH PINE NUTS 
</P>
<P>
 1/2 cup pine nuts 
</P>
<P>
 1 large head green cabbage, coarsely chopped 
</P>
<P>
 1/4 cup unsalted butter, melted 
</P>
<P>
 2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice 
</P>
<P>
 Salt 
</P>
<P>
 Spread pine nuts on baking sheet. Toast at 350 degrees 10 to 12 minutes, until 
golden and fragrant. 
</P>
<P>
 Meanwhile, bring large pot of salted water to boil. Plunge cabbage into water 
and return to boil. Cook 20 seconds. Drain well in colander and transfer to 
warmed bowl. Stir in butter and lemon juice. Season to taste with salt. Toss 
well to combine. Sprinkle roasted pine nuts on top. Toss lightly again before 
serving. Makes 8 servings. 
</P>
<P>
 Each serving contains about: 
</P>
<P>
 130 calories; 58 mg sodium; 15 mg cholesterol; 11 grams fat; 8 grams 
carbohydrates; 4 grams protein; 0.99 gram fiber. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 For simple perfection try this combination of carrots, butter and parsley 
makes a very complete unit.  
</P>
<P>
 PARSLEYED CARROTS 
</P>
<P>
 2 1/2 pounds carrots, peeled and cut on diagonal into 1/2-inch chunks 
</P>
<P>
 1/4 cup unsalted butter 
</P>
<P>
 Salt 
</P>
<P>
 1/4 cup finely chopped parsley 
</P>
<P>
 Bring large saucepan of salted water to boil. Add carrots and cook over 
moderate heat until just tender, about 10 minutes.  
</P>
<P>
 Drain off water. Add butter to saucepan and toss to coat carrots. Season to 
taste with salt. Add parsley and mix well. Transfer to bowl and serve hot. 
Makes 8 servings. 
</P>
<P>
 Each serving contains about: 
</P>
<P>
 105 calories; 82 mg sodium; 15 mg cholesterol; 6 grams fat; 13 grams 
carbohydrates; 1 gram protein; 1.33 grams fiber. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 A tasty complement to the dark meat of a turkey, this dish comes directly from 
the Northeast, the cradle of the Thanksgiving celebration. The maple syrup 
lends a distinct sweetness and seems to heighten the buttered squash flavor. 
For special effect, serve in scooped-out and baked acorn squash halves.  
</P>
<P>
 BAKED SQUASH WITH BUTTER AND MAPLE SYRUP 
</P>
<P>
 6 pounds acorn or butternut squash, halved lengthwise and seeded 
</P>
<P>
 Salt 
</P>
<P>
 Freshly ground pepper 
</P>
<P>
 1/4 cup unsalted butter 
</P>
<P>
 1/4 cup maple syrup 
</P>
<P>
 Place squash cut side down on baking sheet. Bake at 400 degrees 45 minutes to 
1 hour or until squash is easily pierced with fork. Scoop flesh into bowl. Mash 
squash with potato masher or fork until fairly smooth. Season to taste with 
salt and pepper. Keep warm. 
</P>
<P>
 In small saucepan, combine butter and maple syrup and cook over low heat, 
stirring until butter is melted and blended with syrup, about 2 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
 Stir 1/2 of syrup mixture into squash. Transfer squash to shallow serving 
dish. Pour rest of syrup mixture over top. Serve hot. Recipe can be prepared up 
to 2 days ahead. Cover and refrigerate. Reheat in 350-degree oven until hot, 
about 20 minutes. Makes 6 to 8 servings. 
</P>
<P>
 Each serving contains about: 
</P>
<P>
 254 calories; 63 mg sodium; 21 mg cholesterol; 8 grams fat; 48 grams 
carbohydrates; 3 grams protein; 5.36 grams fiber. PEARL ONIONS IN CREAMY ONION 
SAUCE 
</P>
<P>
 1/2 cup unsalted butter 
</P>
<P>
 1 cup dry bread crumbs 
</P>
<P>
 3 medium onions, finely chopped 
</P>
<P>
 1/4 cup flour 
</P>
<P>
 2 cups milk 
</P>
<P>
 2 teaspoons salt 
</P>
<P>
 1/2 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper 
</P>
<P>
 2 (16-ounce) packages frozen small whole onions 
</P>
<P>
 Melt butter in medium saucepan. Pour 1/2 of butter into small bowl. Stir in 
bread crumbs. Set aside. 
</P>
<P>
 Add chopped onions to butter in saucepan. Cook over low heat, stirring 
occasionally, until onions are tender but not brown, about 5 minutes. Sprinkle 
flour over onions. Whisk 1 minute. Increase heat to moderate, slowly add milk. 
Cook, whisking constantly, until sauce is smooth and thickened, about 5 
minutes. Stir in salt and pepper. 
</P>
<P>
 Place onions in 2-quart baking dish. Pour onion sauce over. Mix well, 
spreading onions in even layer. Sprinkle buttered bread crumbs over top. Bake 
at 350 degrees 40 to 50 minutes, or until sauce is bubbling around edges. Serve 
hot. Makes 8 servings. 
</P>
<P>
 Each serving contains about: 
</P>
<P>
 251 calories; 727 mg sodium; 36 mg cholesterol; 13 grams fat; 28 grams 
carbohydrates; 6 grams protein; 1.10 grams fiber. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 This versatile dish is a delicious accompaniment to the Thanksgiving dinner. 
It also makes a lovely winter dessert. Heat with a little Grand Marnier and 
serve over vanilla ice cream.  
</P>
<P>
 WINTER FRUIT COMPOTE 
</P>
<P>
 1 cup pitted prunes, quartered 
</P>
<P>
 1 cup dried apricots, quartered 
</P>
<P>
 1 cup dried apple slices, cut into 1/2-inch pieces 
</P>
<P>
 4 large ripe pears, such as Bartlett or Comice, peeled, cored and cut into 
1/2-inch dice 
</P>
<P>
 1 1/2 cups fresh orange juice 
</P>
<P>
 2 tablespoons brown sugar, packed 
</P>
<P>
 2 teaspoons grated orange zest 
</P>
<P>
 Slivered orange zest 
</P>
<P>
 1/2 cup water 
</P>
<P>
 In large nonreactive saucepan, combine prunes, apricots, apples, pears, orange 
juice, sugar, grated orange zest and water. Bring to boil over high heat. 
Reduce heat to low, cover and simmer until fruits are tender, 7 to 8 minutes. 
Transfer to bowl, garnish with slivered orange zest. Serve warm. Makes 8 to 10 
servings. 
</P>
<P>
 Each serving contains about: 
</P>
<P>
 172 calories; 10 mg sodium; 0 cholesterol; 1 gram fat; 44 grams carbohydrates; 
2 grams protein; 2.25 grams fiber. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 The snappy, sharp flavors of tarragon, capers and vinegar balance the natural 
sweetness of the beets. Tarragon varies in strength, so you may want to add 
more or less, depending on individual taste. This sauce should have a 
pronounced tarragon flavor.  
</P>
<P>
 TARRAGON BEETS 
</P>
<P>
 3 pounds beets, without tops 
</P>
<P>
 Water 
</P>
<P>
 1/3 cup tarragon vinegar 
</P>
<P>
 1 tablespoon finely chopped fresh tarragon or 1 1/2 teaspoons dried 
</P>
<P>
 5 tablespoons unsalted butter 
</P>
<P>
 2 tablespoons drained capers 
</P>
<P>
 Salt 
</P>
<P>
 Freshly ground pepper 
</P>
<P>
 Place beets in large saucepan with water to cover. Bring to boil. Cook until 
tender when pierced with fork, 30 to 40 minutes depending on size of beets. 
Alternatively, wrap beets in foil and bake at 400 degrees about 1 1/4 hours, 
until tender. Peel beets and cut into 1-inch pieces. 
</P>
<P>
 In large nonreactive saucepan, combine 1/4 cup water with vinegar and 
tarragon. Bring to boil over high heat. Reduce heat to moderate and simmer 3 
minutes. Add butter and stir until melted. Add beets and cook, stirring, until 
heated through, about 8 minutes. Remove from heat. Stir in capers. Season to 
taste with salt and pepper. Toss and serve hot. Makes 8 servings. 
</P>
<P>
 Each serving contains about: 
</P>
<P>
 119 calories; 169 mg sodium; 19 mg cholesterol; 7 grams fat; 13 grams 
carbohydrates; 2 grams protein; 0.96 gram fiber. 
</P>
</TEXT>
